rs") (media:description nil "The sun rises above the US Capitol as volunteers place crosses, symbolising grave markers, on the National Mall in Washington. A 24-hour vigil is being held featuring a gathering of Newtown clergy and 3,300 grave markers to 'remind Congress action is needed on gun violence prevention'. The number 3,300 represents the supposed number of people who have died as a result of gun violence since the tragedy at the school in Newtown, Connecticut. Photograph: Kevin Lamarque/Reuters")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/11/1365688066007/4673d8ce-8ee3-480c-8359-8ab12db90d56-460x276.jpeg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Kevin Lamarque/Reuters") (media:description nil "The sun rises earlier this month above the US Capitol as volunteers place crosses, symbolising grave markers, on the National Mall in Washington, to 'remind Congress action is needed on gun violence prevention'. Photograph: Kevin Lamarque/Reuters"))) (item nil (title nil "Boston hospitals: 14 patients still critical but all expected to survive") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/17/boston-bombings-hospital-all-patients-survive") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/18492?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-bombings-hospital-all-patients-survive%3A1895593&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+explosions+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Associated+Press+in+Boston&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+10%3A11&c8=1895593&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=Boston+hospitals%3A+14+patients+still+critical+but+all+expected+to+survive&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+explosions\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Boston Medical Center, Brigham and Women's Hospital and Massachusetts General Hospital expecting all patients will live</p><p>Officials at three Boston hospitals that treated some of the most seriously injured <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/17/boston-bombings-investigation-cctv\">from Monday's bombing at the Boston Marathon</a> said Wednesday they expect all of their patients to survive.</p><p>The trauma surgery chief at Boston Medical Center says a five-year-old boy is among the 19 patients still being treated there for injuries received during the marathon bombings.</p><p>Dr Peter Burke said Wednesday morning that the hospital treated 23 people following the blasts. He said two patients, including the five-year-old, remain critical, but that all patients are making progress.</p><p>\"We have a lot of lower extremity injuries, so I think the damage was low to the ground and wasn't up,\" he said. \"The patients who do have head injuries were blown into things or were hit by fragments that went up.\"</p><p>At least 10 Boston area hospitals treated more than 170 patients following the bombings, and at least 14 were still in critical condition Wednesday. Dozens of patients have been released.</p><p>Massachusetts General Hospital spokeswoman Katie Marquedant said all but 11 of the 31 people sent there have been released. Four were still in critical condition, but she said all of them were expected to live.</p><p>Brigham and Women's Hospital spokesman Tom Langford said his hospital also no longer has any injuries that are considered life threatening. Twelve of the 35 patients it has treated were still there, and four were in critical condition, he said. The hospital originally had reported treating 31 people, but he said others had come into the hospital during the past two days on their own, seeking treatment for bomb-related injuries.</p><p>Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center still has 13 of the 24 people originally sent there.</p><p>Boston Children's Hospital has released seven of its original 10 patients. The three remaining are all children. A two-year-old boy with a head injury is in good condition; a 10-year-old boy with multiple leg injuries is in critical condition and a nine-year-old girl with a leg injury also is in critical condition.</p><p>Tufts Medical Center has released half of its 14 bombing patients.</p><p>Dr Horacio Hojman, the associate chief of trauma at Tufts, said many of the injuries his hospital saw were soft-tissue wounds. He said he was impressed by the attitude of the patients.</p><p>\"Despite what they witnessed, despite what they suffered, despite many of them having life-threatening injuries, their spirits were not broken,\" he said.</p><p>There were 27 patients who were treated at St Elizabeth's, Carney Hospital and Norwood Hospital and released.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon explosions</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon explosions") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 21:11:17 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/17/boston-bombings-hospital-all-patients-survive") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T21:19:12Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407403768") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon explosions, Boston, United States") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366231101465/Boston-Brigham-and-Womens-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Xinhua /Landov / Barcroft Media/Xinhua /Landov / Barcroft Media") (media:description nil "Two policemen guard the Brigham and Women's Hospital where the injured are treated after explosions. Photograph: Xinhua /Landov / Barcroft Media")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366231111948/Boston-Brigham-and-Womens-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Xinhua /Landov / Barcroft Media/Xinhua /Landov / Barcroft Media") (media:description nil "Two policemen guard the Brigham and Women's Hospital where the injured were treated after explosions. Photograph: Barcroft Media"))) (item nil (title nil "Chinese banks top Forbes Global 2000 list of world's biggest companies") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/apr/17/chinese-banks-forbes-global-2000") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/52073?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achinese-banks-forbes-global-2000%3A1895594&ch=Media&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Forbes+magazine%2CBusiness%2CChina+%28News%29%2CUS+news%2CUS+economy+%28Business%29%2CJP+Morgan%2CGeneral+Electric%2CExxon+Mobil%2CApple+%28Technology%29%2CBanking+%28Business+sector%29%2CUtilities+sector+%28Business+sector%29%2CEnergy+industry+%28business+sector%29%2CTechnology+sector+%28business+sector%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets%2CEnergy%2CTechnology+Gadgets%2CUS+Economy%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Dominic+Rushe&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+09%3A37&c8=1895594&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chinese+banks+top+Forbes+Global+2000+list+of+world%27s+biggest+companies&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2FForbes+magazine\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">ICBC and China Construction Bank are Nos 1 and 2, ahead of JP Morgan, General Electric and Exxon, last year's biggest firm</p><p>For the first time, two Chinese firms have topped <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/global2000/\">Forbes magazine's annual poll of the world's largest companies</a>. The Chinese bank ICBC ousted Exxon Mobil as the world's biggest company, according to the magazine's 10th annual ranking of the world's top 2,000 firms. China Construction Bank bumped JP Morgan out of the second spot.</p><p>The US had a total of 543 members in the list this year, 19 more firms than last year and the highest total since 2009. Japan had the second highest number of companies in the list, 251, followed by China with 136. For the first time since 2004, when the list was first published, China did not increase its number of Global 2000 companies.</p><p>The list uses an equal weighting of sales, profits, assets and market value to rank companies according to size. Exxon, last year's No 1, slipped into fourth place this year behind the two Chinese firms, JP Morgan and General Electric. Apple eclipsed Exxon as the most valuable company by market capitalization last year <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/jan/25/exxon-apple-most-valuable-stock\">and the two have vied for pole position ever since</a>. Apple slipped behind Exxon once more on Wednesday. Despite a 24% drop in the Apple share price since last March, Forbes's composite ranking placed Apple at No 15, in a tie with WalMart, the world's largest retailer.</p><p>Banks and other financial-services firms dominate the list, accounting for 469  of the world's top companies, down nine from last year. The next three biggest industries by membership are oil and gas (124), materials (122) and insurance (109).</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/forbes-magazine\">Forbes magazine</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/china\">China</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/useconomy\">US economy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/jpmorgan\">JP Morgan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/generalelectric\">General Electric</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/exxonmobil\">Exxon Mobil</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/apple\">Apple</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/banking\">Banking</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/utilities\">Utilities</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/energy-industry\">Energy industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/technology\">Technology sector</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dominic-rushe\">Dominic Rushe</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Forbes magazine") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Business") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "China") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "US economy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "JP Morgan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "General Electric") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Exxon Mobil") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Apple") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Banking") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Utilities") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Energy industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Technology sector") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 20:37:35 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/apr/17/chinese-banks-forbes-global-2000") (dc:creator nil "Dominic Rushe") (dc:subject nil "Media") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T20:37:35Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407404511") (media:keywords nil "Forbes magazine, Business, China, United States, US economy, JP Morgan, General Electric, Exxon Mobil, Apple, Banking, Utilities, Energy industry, Technology sector") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/7/27/1311777003721/A-Chinese-bank-staff-coun-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "China Newsphoto/REUTERS") (media:description nil "Staff count banknotes at a branch of the China Construction Bank. Photograph: China Newsphoto/REUTERS")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/7/27/1311777007392/A-Chinese-bank-staff-coun-007.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "China Newsphoto/REUTERS") (media:description nil "Staff count banknotes at a branch of the China Construction Bank. Photograph: China Newsphoto/Reuters"))) (item nil (title nil "Supreme court blocks Nigerian activists from suing Shell over alleged torture") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/17/supreme-court-nigerian-activists-shell") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/87262?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Asupreme-court-nigerian-activists-shell%3A1895588&ch=Law&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=US+supreme+court+%28Law%29%2CShell+%28business%29%2CUS+news%2CUS+foreign+policy%2CHuman+rights%2CUS+constitution+and+civil+liberties+%28Law%29%2CObama+administration%2CWorld+news%2CNigeria+%28News%29%2CLaw&c5=Business+Markets%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUS+Elections&c6=Dominic+Rushe&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+09%3A29&c8=1895588&c9=Article&c10=&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=Supreme+court+blocks+Nigerian+activists+from+suing+Shell+over+alleged+torture&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FUS+supreme+court\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Nigerians had hoped to use US Alien Tort Statute to sue Royal Dutch Petroleum over the deaths of nine protesters in the 1990s</p><p>The supreme court has blocked a group of Nigerians from suing the oil giant Shell in US court for allegedly aiding in torture and murder in a ruling that human rights experts warned could limit the ability to bring such cases in the US.</p><p>In a unanimous ruling, the justices stopped a case filed by Nigerian activists now living in the US who allege that in the 1990s Royal Dutch Petroleum was <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2009/may/27/ken-saro-wiwa-shell-oil\">complicit in the the torture and murder of protesters</a> at the company's Shell Oil operations in the Ogoni region.</p><p>The unanimous decision affirmed a lower court ruling that the Alien Tort Statute (ATS), written in 1789, cannot be used to sue foreign entities for alleged violations of international law on foreign soil. \"Nothing in the ATS's text evinces a clear indication of extraterritorial reach,\" the court found.</p><p>Esther Kiobel, the lead plaintiff in the case, is the wife of the late Dr Barinem Kiobel, one of a group of Nigerian environmental activists known as the Ogoni Nine, who protested against the devastating impact of Shell's operations in the Niger Delta. In 1995 the Ogoni Nine were tortured and hanged by the Nigerian military junta.</p><p>The Center for Constitutional Rights (CCR) said it was \"deeply troubled by the supreme court's decision to undercut 30 years of jurisprudence to limit US courts' ability to hear cases on human rights violations committed outside the United States\".</p><p>\"The US with this case is withdrawing from the world from the path that international law has taken,\" said Peter Weiss, vice-president of the CCR, said. He said it was \"in the national interest\" for the US to promote human rights around the world.</p><p>Peter Rees, Shell's legal director, said: \"In our view, the court has reached the right decision. Shell remains firmly committed to supporting fundamental human rights in line with the legitimate role of business, and I want to make clear that we deny, in the strongest possible terms, the allegations made by the plaintiffs in this tragic case. Today's decision doesn't weaken the human rights of people around the world; it makes it clear that the Alien Tort Statute does not provide a means for claims to be brought in the US which have nothing to do with the US.</p><p>\"But we've always maintained this case has nothing to do with the United States. The Alien Tort Statute is an 18th Century law designed for an entirely different purpose and certainly not for application where there is no connection with the United States. We appreciate the opportunity to have been heard in this case, and we are pleased that the court has now clarified this area of the law.\"</p><p>The US Chamber of Commerce praised the decision. \"The US supreme court's decision today ensures that trial lawyers cannot continue to use the American judicial system to expose global businesses to frivolous and costly lawsuits,\" said president Thomas Donohue. \"Today's decision helps to ensure that America will continue to be an attractive place to do business and removes barriers for companies looking to do business throughout the world.\"</p><p>The ATS has been a popular vehicle for human rights cases since 1980 when Joelito Filártiga, son of a Paraguayan opposition figure who was tortured and killed by Paraguayan police, sued his father's torturer in the US courts. Filártiga was denied justice at home but sued in the US when he learned his father's torturer was living in New York.  A US court held that torturers, like pirates, had become \"hostis humani generis\" – enemies of all mankind.</p><p>Marco Simons, legal director of EarthRights, a human rights nonprofit,  said the ruling left many questions unanswered. EarthRights is currently leading a case against banana giant Chiquita Brands for allegedly funding terrorists in Columbia. As a US company Simons said the new ruling would not affect the case Chiquita.</p><p>\"It's clear in other areas of the law that any foreign company doing business in the US has to abide by US standards. For the ATS there is now a two tier system,\" he said. Simons said he expected Congress would have to address the imbalance and that the ruling was likely to lead to more not less litigation.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/us-supreme-court\">US supreme court</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/royaldutchshell\">Royal Dutch Shell</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usforeignpolicy\">US foreign policy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/human-rights\">Human rights</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/us-constitution-and-civil-liberties\">US constitution and civil liberties</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/obama-administration\">Obama administration</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/nigeria\">Nigeria</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dominic-rushe\">Dominic Rushe</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "US supreme court") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Royal Dutch Shell") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US foreign policy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Human rights") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "US constitution and civil liberties") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Obama administration") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Nigeria") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Editorial") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 20:29:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/17/supreme-court-nigerian-activists-shell") (dc:creator nil "Dominic Rushe") (dc:subject nil "Law") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T21:29:20Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407402454") (media:keywords nil "US supreme court, Royal Dutch Shell, United States, US foreign policy, Human rights, US constitution and civil liberties, Obama administration, World news, Nigeria, Law") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366229415226/shell-us-court-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Adam Berry/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Nigerian activists now living in the US allege that in the 1990s the company was complicit in the the torture and murder of protesters. Photograph: Adam Berry/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366229424742/shell-us-court-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Adam Berry/Getty Images") (media:description nil "In 1995 the Ogoni Nine protesting Shell's operations were tortured and hanged by the Nigerian military junta. Photograph: Adam Berry/Getty Images"))))) ("Boston bombing suspects: what we know" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/88943?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev%3A1897058&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CDzhokhar+Tsarnaev%2CTamerlan+Tsarnaev%2CFBI%2CChechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CKyrgyzstan+%28News%29%2CUS+news%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CCrime+%28US%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Guardian&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A41&c8=1897058&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Boston+bombing+suspects%3A+what+we+know&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev is seriously injured, while his brother Tamerlan was killed in a firefight. Little is known of their lives</p><p>Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, 19, remains in a Boston hospital seriously injured and unable to speak, while his brother, Tamerlan, 26, was killed in a firefight with police on Friday. Although many aspects of their lives remain sketchy, some facts have been established:</p><p></p><p><strong>1986</strong></p><p>Tamerlan is born in Kyrgyzstan in central Asia.</p><p></p><p><strong>1993</strong></p><p>Dzhokar is born in Kyrgyzstan, according to local media, or Dagestan, according to relatives in the US.</p><p></p><p><strong>1990s</strong></p><p>The brothers grow up in a small community of Chechens in Kyrgyzstan.</p><p></p><p><strong>1999-2001</strong></p><p>The family moves to Dagestan, a Muslim republic neighbouring Chechnya, some time between 1999 and 2001.</p><p></p><p><strong>2001</strong></p><p>Dzhokar attends School Number One in Makhachkala, Dagestan's capital, according to Irina Bandurina, an administrator at the school.</p><p>The two brothers reportedly spend five months in Dagestan from September 2001 until March 2002.</p><p></p><p><strong>2002</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar and his parents move to the US in 2002. They settle in Cambridge, Massachusetts, where the father, Anzor Tsarnaev, opens a garage.</p><p></p><p><strong>2004</strong></p><p>Tamerlan and his two sisters, Alina and Bella, arrive in the US to join the rest of the family.</p><p></p><p><strong>2006</strong></p><p>Tamerlan studies accounting as a part-time student at Bunker Hill Community College in Boston for three terms from 2006 to 2008, the school said. According to reports, at some time in this period he married Katherine Russell, a US citizen. The couple have a child.</p><p></p><p><strong>2009</strong></p><p>Ruslan Tsarni, uncle of the Tsarnaev brothers, said he had a falling-out with Tamerlan over his increased commitment to Islam. He said Tamerlan told him in a 2009 phone conversation that he had chosen \"God's business\" over work or school.</p><p>Tamerlan is arrested when police are called to a report of domestic violence.</p><p>Tamerlan, a keen boxer, represents New England in the Golden Gloves competition in 2009 and the following year.</p><p></p><p><strong>2010</strong></p><p>According to the FBI, a foreign government reports that Tamerlan appears to be a radical Muslim and strong believer and that he is preparing to leave the US for travel to the Russian region.</p><p></p><p><strong>2011</strong></p><p>The FBI said it interviewed Tamerlan in 2011 but did not find any \"terrorism activity\" at that time.</p><p></p><p><strong>2011</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar graduates from school in Boston. He receives a scholarship to the University of Massachusetts Dartmouth.</p><p></p><p><strong>2012</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar, his mother and father become US citizens. Tamerlan's application for citizenship is reportedly delayed after a background check shows he was interviewed in 2011 by the FBI.</p><p>Tamerlan travels to Moscow in January and spends six months in the region. His father, Anzor Tsarnaev, said his son had mostly stayed with him at his home in Makhachkala, but that the two men had also visited Chechnya.</p><p>On 14 March <a href=\"https://twitter.com/J_tsar/status/179877765070323712\" title=\"\">Dzhokhar tweets: \"a decade in america already, i want out.\"</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/dzhokhar-tsarnaev\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/tamerlan-tsarnaev\">Tamerlan Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/fbi\">FBI</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/kyrgyzstan\">Kyrgyzstan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/boston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev" (20852 2226) old 8 nil nil ((title nil "Boston bombing suspects: what we know") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/boston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/88943?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev%3A1897058&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CDzhokhar+Tsarnaev%2CTamerlan+Tsarnaev%2CFBI%2CChechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CKyrgyzstan+%28News%29%2CUS+news%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CCrime+%28US%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Guardian&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A41&c8=1897058&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Boston+bombing+suspects%3A+what+we+know&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev is seriously injured, while his brother Tamerlan was killed in a firefight. Little is known of their lives</p><p>Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, 19, remains in a Boston hospital seriously injured and unable to speak, while his brother, Tamerlan, 26, was killed in a firefight with police on Friday. Although many aspects of their lives remain sketchy, some facts have been established:</p><p></p><p><strong>1986</strong></p><p>Tamerlan is born in Kyrgyzstan in central Asia.</p><p></p><p><strong>1993</strong></p><p>Dzhokar is born in Kyrgyzstan, according to local media, or Dagestan, according to relatives in the US.</p><p></p><p><strong>1990s</strong></p><p>The brothers grow up in a small community of Chechens in Kyrgyzstan.</p><p></p><p><strong>1999-2001</strong></p><p>The family moves to Dagestan, a Muslim republic neighbouring Chechnya, some time between 1999 and 2001.</p><p></p><p><strong>2001</strong></p><p>Dzhokar attends School Number One in Makhachkala, Dagestan's capital, according to Irina Bandurina, an administrator at the school.</p><p>The two brothers reportedly spend five months in Dagestan from September 2001 until March 2002.</p><p></p><p><strong>2002</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar and his parents move to the US in 2002. They settle in Cambridge, Massachusetts, where the father, Anzor Tsarnaev, opens a garage.</p><p></p><p><strong>2004</strong></p><p>Tamerlan and his two sisters, Alina and Bella, arrive in the US to join the rest of the family.</p><p></p><p><strong>2006</strong></p><p>Tamerlan studies accounting as a part-time student at Bunker Hill Community College in Boston for three terms from 2006 to 2008, the school said. According to reports, at some time in this period he married Katherine Russell, a US citizen. The couple have a child.</p><p></p><p><strong>2009</strong></p><p>Ruslan Tsarni, uncle of the Tsarnaev brothers, said he had a falling-out with Tamerlan over his increased commitment to Islam. He said Tamerlan told him in a 2009 phone conversation that he had chosen \"God's business\" over work or school.</p><p>Tamerlan is arrested when police are called to a report of domestic violence.</p><p>Tamerlan, a keen boxer, represents New England in the Golden Gloves competition in 2009 and the following year.</p><p></p><p><strong>2010</strong></p><p>According to the FBI, a foreign government reports that Tamerlan appears to be a radical Muslim and strong believer and that he is preparing to leave the US for travel to the Russian region.</p><p></p><p><strong>2011</strong></p><p>The FBI said it interviewed Tamerlan in 2011 but did not find any \"terrorism activity\" at that time.</p><p></p><p><strong>2011</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar graduates from school in Boston. He receives a scholarship to the University of Massachusetts Dartmouth.</p><p></p><p><strong>2012</strong></p><p>Dzhokhar, his mother and father become US citizens. Tamerlan's application for citizenship is reportedly delayed after a background check shows he was interviewed in 2011 by the FBI.</p><p>Tamerlan travels to Moscow in January and spends six months in the region. His father, Anzor Tsarnaev, said his son had mostly stayed with him at his home in Makhachkala, but that the two men had also visited Chechnya.</p><p>On 14 March <a href=\"https://twitter.com/J_tsar/status/179877765070323712\" title=\"\">Dzhokhar tweets: \"a decade in america already, i want out.\"</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/dzhokhar-tsarnaev\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/tamerlan-tsarnaev\">Tamerlan Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/fbi\">FBI</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/kyrgyzstan\">Kyrgyzstan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon bombing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Tamerlan Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "FBI") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Kyrgyzstan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 15:41:38 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/boston-bombing-suspects-dzhokhar-tamerlan-tsarnaev") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T15:51:38Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407597205") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, Tamerlan Tsarnaev, FBI, Chechnya, Russia, Kyrgyzstan, United States, Massachusetts, US crime, Boston, World news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366558138370/Boston-bombing-suspects-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Uncredited/AP") (media:description nil "Boston bombing suspects Tamerlan Tsarnaev, left, and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev. Photograph: Uncredited/AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366558144330/Boston-bombing-suspects-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Uncredited/AP") (media:description nil "Boston bombing suspects Tamerlan Tsarnaev, left, and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev. Photograph: Uncredited/AP")))) ("FBI accused of 'dropping the ball' on prior questioning of Tamerlan Tsarnaev" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/63609?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Afbi-tamerlan-tsarnaev-questioning%3A1897055&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CFBI%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CUS+Congress%2CUS+politics%2CDzhokhar+Tsarnaev%2CTamerlan+Tsarnaev&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUS+Elections&c6=Matt+Williams&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A31&c8=1897055&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=FBI+accused+of+%27dropping+the+ball%27+on+prior+questioning+of+Tamerlan+Tsarnaev&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Members of Congress ask why no flags were raised after FBI was asked to interview elder Tsarnaev brother in 2011</p><p>The FBI was facing increased scrutiny Sunday over its prior handling of a case involving suspected Boston bomber Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with senior congressional figures demanding answers and accusing the agency of \"dropping the ball\".</p><p>As younger brother Dzhokhar remained in hospital yet to be questioned or charged, Tamerlan – who was killed in a shootout with police early Friday – has been seen by many as the key to understanding how the pair seemingly became radicalised.</p><p>It is now known that the FBI interviewed the elder Tsarnaev brother in 2011 at the request of the Russian government, which raised concern that he had links to Chechen terrorists. On Sunday rebels in the strife-torn country denied any link. But a six-month visit to Russia last year is now being scrutinised to see if Tsarnaev did visit any other countries in the North Caucuses region.</p><p>Michael McCaul, chair of the House Homeland Security Committee, told CNN's State of the Union on Sunday that the FBI had questions to answer.</p><p>\"He was interviewed by the FBI in 2011 and let go. He travelled back to Russia and spent six months there,\" McCaul said.</p><p>On return he immediately posted jihadist videos on YouTube, the Republican lawmaker said. \"Clearly something happened in that six-month timeframe. He radicalised at some point.\"</p><p>McCaul said he wanted to know why no flags were raised on Tsarnaev that would have helped officials track his movements.</p><p>Meanwhile it was reported Sunday that a hold was placed on a citizenship request by the 26-year-old as a result of the FBI's former interest in him.</p><p>An article in the New York Times claimed officials at the Department of Homeland Security decided not to grant his application after a routine background check uncovered the 2011 interview by agents.</p><p>The FBI has not said publicly who requested that they look into the activities of the elder brother, but it has been widely reported that it was the Russian government.</p><p>In a statement late Friday, the agency admitted interviewing Tamerlan and other family members.</p><p>\"The FBI did not find any terrorism activity, domestic of foreign, and those results were provided to the foreign government in the summer of 2011,\" it said.</p><p>But on Sunday, the agency was accused of having \"dropped the ball\" regarding the older Tsarnaev brother.</p><p>\"The FBI missed a lot of things is one potential answer, or laws do not allow the FBI to follow up in a sound, solid way,\" senator Lindsey Graham told CNN's State of the Union.</p><p>Meanwhile fellow Republican Peter King, chairman of the House subcommittee on counterterrorism, blasted the FBI for alleged failings in the case.</p><p>\"This is the firth case I'm aware of where the FBI has failed to stop someone,\" he told Fox News Sunday, going on to cite the cases of al-Qaida recruiter Anwar al-Awlaki, Little Rock shooter Carlos Bledsoe, the accused Fort Hood killer Nidal Malik and alleged American-Pakistani terrorist David Coleman Headley.</p><p>\"This is the latest in a series of cases like this … where the FBI is given information about someone as being a potential terrorist. They look at them, and then hey don't take action and then they go out and commit murders,\" King said.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/fbi\">FBI</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/congress\">US Congress</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-politics\">US politics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/dzhokhar-tsarnaev\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/tamerlan-tsarnaev\">Tamerlan Tsarnaev</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/matt-williams\">Matt Williams</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/fbi-tamerlan-tsarnaev-questioning" (20852 1588) old 9 nil nil ((title nil "FBI accused of 'dropping the ball' on prior questioning of Tamerlan Tsarnaev") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/21/fbi-tamerlan-tsarnaev-questioning") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/63609?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Afbi-tamerlan-tsarnaev-questioning%3A1897055&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CFBI%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CUS+Congress%2CUS+politics%2CDzhokhar+Tsarnaev%2CTamerlan+Tsarnaev&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUS+Elections&c6=Matt+Williams&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+04%3A31&c8=1897055&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=FBI+accused+of+%27dropping+the+ball%27+on+prior+questioning+of+Tamerlan+Tsarnaev&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Members of Congress ask why no flags were raised after FBI was asked to interview elder Tsarnaev brother in 2011</p><p>The FBI was facing increased scrutiny Sunday over its prior handling of a case involving suspected Boston bomber Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with senior congressional figures demanding answers and accusing the agency of \"dropping the ball\".</p><p>As younger brother Dzhokhar remained in hospital yet to be questioned or charged, Tamerlan – who was killed in a shootout with police 